For your **file system statics** (`File.*`, `Directory.*`), the best approach is the battle-tested **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — no custom wrappers needed.

### 1. Install the packages

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers  # in your test project
```

### 2. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling statics

Refactor `ReportGenerator` (and similar classes) to take `IFileSystem` via constructor injection:

```csharp
using System.IO.Abstractions;

public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var outputDir = Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}.txt");
        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, $"Report: {reportName}");

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

### 3. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.Directory.CreateDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
var path = generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.That(mockFs.File.Exists(path), Is.True);
Assert.That(mockFs.File.ReadAllText(path), Does.Contain("sales"));
```

`MockFileSystem` gives you an in-memory file system — no temp files, no cleanup, fully deterministic.

---

> **Bonus:** I also see `DateTime.UtcNow` and `Environment.*` statics in `ReportGenerator.cs`. Since you're on **.NET 10**, you can use the built-in **`TimeProvider`** for time, and a small custom `IEnvironmentProvider` wrapper for environment calls. Want me to show those too, or migrate the file system calls in your code?
